Unfortunately I don't have any of the proprietary simulators handy to verify it, but IIRC there the `addr_wtf` would be delayed by one clock cycle w.r.t. `addr`. While in fact in Verilator it acts as continuous assignment (combinatorial).

```systemverilog
module top;

   localparam int unsigned STEP = 10;
   localparam int unsigned ADDR_WIDTH = 3;

   logic aclock = 0, areset_n = 0;
   logic [ADDR_WIDTH - 1 : 0] addr;
   logic [ADDR_WIDTH - 1 : 0] addr_wtf;

   always #(STEP / 2) aclock = ~aclock;

   initial
     begin
        $dumpfile ("dump.vcd");
        $dumpvars;

        $write ("Resetting... ");
        #(STEP * 10) areset_n = 1;
        $display ("done");
        #(STEP * 10);

        for (int a = 0; a != 1 << ADDR_WIDTH; a++)
          begin
             addr = a[ADDR_WIDTH - 1 : 0];
             @(posedge aclock);
          end

        #(STEP * 1000) $finish;
     end

   always_ff @(posedge aclock)
     addr_wtf <= addr;

endmodule : top

// verilatoR --binary --cc --timing --trace --top top assignment.sv
// obj_dir/Vtop
// gtkwave dump.vcd
```
I'm not sure what I'm doing wrong here^, but it seems like the behavior is incorrect.
```shell
$ verilator --version  # NixOS
Verilator 5.012 2023-06-13 rev UNKNOWN.REV
```
